column2: Historic Marietta Square - 65 Church Street NW, Marietta, GA 30060
column17: The Marietta Square Farmers Market aims to support the local agricultural economy by providing a platform for farmers and vendors to sell high-quality, handmade products directly to consumers. It helps food and garden-related businesses using locally grown ingredients access the market, promoting community engagement and offering an alternative shopping experience. All products sold are grown or produced by the vendors themselves. Considered #1 best farmers market in Atlanta.
column19: Over 65 vendors, ranging from fruits and vegetables to home goods and kitchen staples. Arrive empty handed and leave with everything you need to make from-scratch meals at home. You can even dress your dinner table with freshly cut local flowers. Source: <https://www.mariettasquarefarmersmarket.com/press.html>.
column20:
Established Customer Base: Being the #1 farmers market in Atlanta ensures consistent foot traffic and a ready market for your goods.
 
 Low Entry Cost: At $25 per week, it offers an affordable way to reach customers compared to other retail options.
 
 In- and Off-Season Sales: Year-round market enables to sell regardless of seasonality
column21:
Time Commitment: Requires weekly presence on Saturdays, including setup and breakdown time.
 
 Logistical Challenges: Location is in Marietta, relatively distant from metro Atlanta
 
 Alcohol Prohibition: No Alcohol Policy inhibits using syrup in sample alcoholic drinks
column22:
Planning: organize time commitment and schedule logistics beforehand
 
 Alcohol alternatives: use cocktail syrups for virgin drinks

column23:
2025 Applications Open December 17th 2024
 
 Guidelines: <https://cfmatl.org/become-a-vendor/>.
 
 Application Fees
 
 First Time Applicants: If you are a First-Time Applicant or have never been accepted as a full season vendor at a CFM market before, the initial application fee is $100.00 for one market and $50.00 for each additional market(s) you would like to apply for. 
 
 Returning Vendors: If you are a Returning Vendor (having sold at one or more CFM markets last season) the application fee is $50.00 for one market and $25.00 for each additional market(s) you would like to apply for. All vendors are required to resubmit applications and fees at the start of each season.
 
 New Vendor Application Fee Discount Form: CFM is providing financial assistance for businesses operated by socially and/or historically disenfranchised persons or groups. If interested, please fill out this form to request a discount on your application fee before completing your vendor application. (available only during open application period)

column1: Piedmont Park Conservancy Green Market – Farm to Park
column12:
$30 per week
 
 Discount: 10% discount for those who pay in full and plan to attend the market for the entire 34
 weeks.
column16:
Application Fee: $40
 
 Liability Insurance: minimum of $1 million in coverage is required by all vendors. A copy of the certificate of insurance must be provided upon notification of acceptance prior to attending the market
column17: Market encourages sustainable communities in the most basic way – by providing shoppers with direct access to local farmers and small businesses. Enjoy local farmers, bakers, jams, preserves and artisan goods. There is something for everyone. While you shop, you can enjoy prepared foods and drinks for breakfast and lunch.
column19: Green Market focuses mainly on consumable food products, prioritizing locally farmed produce, meat, eggs, and dairy. It also features prepared foods, artisanal grocery items, and a selection of handmade jewelry, arts, and crafts. Other product categories and promotional activities may be permitted on a case-by-case basis, with sponsorship opportunities available through the market manager.
column20:

column21:

column6: Saturdays 9:00am - 12:00pm (1st and 3rd Saturdays of each month; October - May)
column17:
The Snellville Farmers’ Market is administered by a group of very dedicated local residents, many of whom volunteer their time and talents to bring the market to the city. The market operates without any funding from the city. The city does, however, allow the market to operate on the Towne Green, a prime location in front of City Hall where the market has outstanding exposure to traffic on US 78 and Oak Road.
 
 The mission of the Snellville Farmers’ Market is:
 
 To “Nourish Our Community” by providing fresh, local and seasonal produce and encouraging community pride.

column2: 99 Centennial Olympic Park Dr. SW, Atlanta, GA 30313
column12:
$35 per week
 
Discount: 20% discount is provided for vendors wishing to pay for the entire season upfront.
column17: Under the Westside Farmers Markets umbrella, Castleberry Market, Fickett Farmers Market, and Underground Atlanta Farmers Markets work together to bring fresh, locally produced food to underserved neighborhoods in southwest and west Atlanta. Our goal is to support and nourish our community by sourcing substantial amounts of food from Georgia growers and producers. We are committed to creating opportunities for local makers, producers, and growers to thrive as entrepreneurs, while actively serving and supporting our community.

column17: This market is small, but mighty. Located in the shady parking lot in front of Lang Carson Community Center, the market is within walking distance of our entire neighborhood and just 100 yards off the Beltline. We put out a survey on social media asking folks if they’d like a market, and within a few days we had over 450 responses with a resounding yes!
column19: We have a strong sense of community and a deep communication reach with our residents. We host a variety of booths, including produce, eggs & dairy, meat, bread, prepared foods, ready-to-eat food vendors and non-food items. Our vendors change from week to week, so keep in touch here and on socials to see who will be joining us!
column20:
Prime Location Near the Beltline: Being close to the Atlanta Beltline offers potential visibility to passersby and may attract a mix of local residents and casual visitors, increasing foot traffic and brand exposure
 
 Variety of Vendors: With a rotating roster of vendors, Farmers Jam can benefit from drawing in different types of customers each week
column21:

column22: Marketing: Capitalize on social media, tagging the market and partnering with influencers in the area to broaden Farmers Jam’s reach. Farmers Jam can promote its attendance in advance on social media to draw attention from followers

column19: variety of vegetables, fruits, eggs and meat, flowers, artisan crafts, and prepared foods. We have live music to enjoy at each market and a free children’s activity. We are proud to double SNAP dollars with the support of Wholesome Wave Georgia.
column20:
Community and Family Appeal: The market promotes a strong community connection, and the inclusion of live music and children’s activities draws families, which could enhance Farmers Jam’s brand as a family-friendly, community-oriented business
 
 Seasonal Full Vendor Membership Option: The option to pay $943 for the entire season could provide Farmers Jam with significant savings if they plan to attend every Saturday
 
 Early Morning Hours: The 8 am to 12 pm timeframe allows Farmers Jam to reach early risers, which could attract a steady morning crowd and finish early enough to allow for other weekend commitments.
 
 Proximity to Athens Community: Athens has a dedicated local following for community events and farmers markets, allowing Farmers Jam to build brand recognition with residents who prioritize local and artisanal products.
column21:
Distance from Atlanta: Traveling to Athens each week could increase transportation costs and time, especially if gas prices are high.
 
 Early Start Requirement: Setting up by 8 am may require an early start, which could be logistically challenging
column22:
Transportation Alternatives: Plan efficient inventory to minimize restocking trips, or consider carpooling with another vendor traveling from Atlanta
 
 Eventual Partnerships: To ease the early mornings, Farmers Jam could arrange alternating schedules if multiple team members are available or partner with a local assistant in Athens.
